docs.abstract: Ms. Harris has appeal for black voters. But she also faces challenges — skepticism about her background as a prosecutor, overcoming sexism and competing in a crowded primary field.
docs.snippet: Ms. Harris has appeal for black voters. But she also faces challenges — skepticism about her background as a prosecutor, overcoming sexism and competing in a crowded primary field.
docs.lead_paragraph: COLUMBIA, S.C. — As Senator Kamala Harris attempts her own version of former President Barack Obama’s historic rise from first-term senator to the White House, one of her political tests will be trying to secure the overwhelming support from black voters that buoyed Mr. Obama in 2008. Ms. Harris wants that support, but it does not come automatically.

headline.main: Can Kamala Harris Repeat Obama’s Success With Black Voters? It’s Complicated
headline.print_headline: An Obama-Like Path, but With Tests of Her Own

docs.abstract: With issues of race percolating in the N.F.L., several players reflect on Martin Luther King Jr. and his protest movement.
docs.snippet: With issues of race percolating in the N.F.L., several players reflect on Martin Luther King Jr. and his protest movement.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — It is doubtful that the N.F.L. owners understood, when they decided early in 2016 to play the Super Bowl here, how the city of Atlanta, as the cradle of the civil rights movement, would serve as a natural forum for the many complicated social and racial issues that have roiled the league in recent years.

headline.main: Atlanta Stokes a Civil Rights Conversation for Some Super Bowl Players
headline.print_headline: Patriots Become Pilgrims in Civil Rights Mecca

docs.abstract: This new Showtime comedy is unapologetically vulgar, but it aims to amount to more than just a bunch of dirty jokes.

docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Cocaine has disrupted countless Hollywood productions, and that was the case not long ago on the set of Showtime’s new comedy “Black Monday.” But this time, it was its absence, not its presence, that was the problem.

headline.main: ‘Black Monday’ Mines ’80s Excess for Comedy and Commentary

docs.abstract: What does it mean for Nike to align itself with Colin Kaepernick?
docs.snippet: What does it mean for Nike to align itself with Colin Kaepernick?
docs.lead_paragraph: Last fall, Nike released a groundbreaking ad featuring the former N.F.L. quarterback Colin Kaepernick. His kneeling protest, which started in 2016 as a response to police brutality, was reinterpreted by social media, celebrities and Nike itself to mean something that doesn’t always match the intention of his original protest. So what does it say that a multinational corporation has aligned itself with a social movement? And are we O.K. with this form of “Kaepitalism”?

docs.abstract: Mr. Heyward became an activist after his 13-year-old son, who was playing with a toy gun, was killed by a police officer in Brooklyn in 1994.
docs.snippet: Mr. Heyward became an activist after his 13-year-old son, who was playing with a toy gun, was killed by a police officer in Brooklyn in 1994.
docs.lead_paragraph: One September evening in 1994, Nicholas Heyward Jr., 13, was playing cops and robbers with friends on a rooftop at the Gowanus Houses, the Brooklyn housing project where he lived. The boys, carrying toy guns, decided to go back inside and rushed down the stairs, jostling one another.

headline.main: Nicholas Heyward Sr., 61, Dies; Spoke Out Against Police Brutality
headline.print_headline: Nicholas Heyward Sr., 61, Police Brutality Protester

docs.abstract: The literary figure is the glowing subject of a group exhibition, curated by the New Yorker critic Hilton Als, that is part personal narrative, part study of his influence on contemporary artists.
docs.snippet: The literary figure is the glowing subject of a group exhibition, curated by the New Yorker critic Hilton Als, that is part personal narrative, part study of his influence on contemporary artists.
docs.lead_paragraph: “My father said, during all the years I lived with him, that I was the ugliest boy he had ever seen, and I had absolutely no reason to doubt him.” So wrote James Baldwin in 1976, and he repeated his father’s words often. He did have reason to doubt them though. They didn’t jibe with my impression of the writer’s appearance as taken from a photograph on the cover of the 1955 paperback edition of “Notes of a Native Son,” which I owned and treasured when I was a teenager, and a copy of which you’ll find on display toward the start of the exhibition “God Made My Face: A Collective Portrait of James Baldwin” at David Zwirner.

headline.print_headline: Under the Influence of James Baldwin
